[ Inaudible Remark ]

00:46:59.216 --> 00:47:03.226
&gt;&gt; Yeah, you know, I happen
to be one of those students

00:47:03.476 --> 00:47:06.336
at the time when I
started undergrad at UCLA.

00:47:06.776 --> 00:47:08.826
Coming from Los Angles
or South LA,

00:47:08.826 --> 00:47:11.676
I didn't have access
to resources, right?

00:47:11.676 --> 00:47:13.486
And I have a family
member I could pick

00:47:13.486 --> 00:47:14.836
on the phone and call them.

00:47:15.196 --> 00:47:17.346
In fact, because I was receiving
financially they would often

00:47:17.346 --> 00:47:19.076
call me and say, "Hey
can you help us out?

00:47:19.076 --> 00:47:20.716
We don't have anything to eat."

00:47:20.716 --> 00:47:22.596
And so having been
in that situation,

00:47:22.596 --> 00:47:24.136
I understand how
difficult it was.

00:47:24.636 --> 00:47:27.606
I would work 30 to 40 hours
a week get in and out, right?

00:47:27.936 --> 00:47:30.086
Sometimes that would be
my only meal for the day.

00:47:30.306 --> 00:47:33.486
So I know how challenging
it can be as a student to go

00:47:33.486 --> 00:47:37.406
through that and I think one of
the strategies that I was able

00:47:37.406 --> 00:47:40.446
to utilize to both to get
support that I needed,

00:47:40.446 --> 00:47:42.726
but to also be OK with that was

00:47:42.726 --> 00:47:45.186
to approach my councilors,
right?

00:47:45.506 --> 00:47:48.766
I had this amazing
councilor, two actually,

00:47:49.106 --> 00:47:53.026
one was named Shelley Benton
and our academic supports

00:47:53.026 --> 00:47:55.806
or academic services in the
College of Letters and Science

00:47:55.806 --> 00:47:58.056
at UCLA who took the
time to get to know me,

00:47:58.056 --> 00:48:00.716
to get to know my needs, and to
understand what those needs were

00:48:00.966 --> 00:48:02.456
and provided advice
and direction.

00:48:02.796 --> 00:48:04.596
The other person was
my [inaudible] mentors

00:48:05.566 --> 00:48:07.026
in the academic advancement
program

00:48:07.026 --> 00:48:08.526
at UCLA who did the same.

00:48:08.826 --> 00:48:10.436
So it's by building
relationships

00:48:10.436 --> 00:48:13.536
with these ombudsmen, so
to speak, these people

00:48:13.536 --> 00:48:16.066
on our campuses who
interact direct with students

00:48:16.066 --> 00:48:18.616
and letting me know about the
resources that were available

00:48:18.826 --> 00:48:20.596
and I was able to get
the support I needed.

00:48:20.596 --> 00:48:25.516
And I think, in many ways the--
it starts with and I think most

00:48:25.516 --> 00:48:27.456
of the panelist here would
probably agree but it starts

00:48:27.456 --> 00:48:28.716
and ends with relationships.

00:48:28.936 --> 00:48:32.096
If you don't have relationships
with students in the institution

00:48:32.386 --> 00:48:34.476
or you don't have relationship
with people in the community

00:48:34.656 --> 00:48:36.406
or you're not able to
build solid relationships

00:48:36.406 --> 00:48:36.996
with each other.

00:48:36.996 --> 00:48:38.836
You're not going to
get good work done.

00:48:39.586 --> 00:48:41.626
And so I think it's
beginning to focus on--

00:48:41.626 --> 00:48:42.706
so we want to get
through stigma,

00:48:42.706 --> 00:48:45.486
you got to start building
relationships with those who are

00:48:45.486 --> 00:48:48.406
in need, but having the
mechanisms to do that

00:48:48.406 --> 00:48:51.376
and be able to scale up the
systems that are discovered

00:48:51.376 --> 00:48:53.236
through those processes.

