00:53:55.786 --> 00:53:59.326
&gt;&gt; The next question, also
on the international policy,

00:53:59.726 --> 00:54:04.666
is NAFTA is an example of a
financial incentive to divest

00:54:04.666 --> 00:54:06.326
of local food independence.

00:54:06.656 --> 00:54:09.336
Similar financial trends
are well established

00:54:09.336 --> 00:54:12.926
in the first world countries
and in university food systems.

00:54:13.176 --> 00:54:16.336
Are there financial
incentives or economic models

00:54:16.766 --> 00:54:19.986
that could work the other
way other than patches

00:54:19.986 --> 00:54:21.546
such as charitable
food handouts?

00:54:21.546 --> 00:54:28.876
&gt;&gt; You know, I think it's
the million dollar question.

00:54:28.876 --> 00:54:31.346
Really, what I hear in that
question is what can we do

00:54:31.346 --> 00:54:34.886
to shift our local foods-- ship
to a local food system, right?

00:54:34.886 --> 00:54:36.946
I mean, that's fundamentally
what it's about.

00:54:36.946 --> 00:54:39.186
And often what you will
find since I grow food

00:54:39.186 --> 00:54:41.626
in the community and we have a
community supportive agriculture

00:54:41.966 --> 00:54:44.916
program, we have been wrestling
with this for quite sometime.

00:54:45.386 --> 00:54:48.906
What I find is that institutions
like UC Santa Barbara, UCLA,

00:54:48.906 --> 00:54:50.106
UC Berkeley, et cetera.

00:54:50.646 --> 00:54:54.996
LAUSD, et cetera, they all
have issues with scale, right?

00:54:55.296 --> 00:54:59.456
So to feed 750,000 students
in LAUSD, you have to be able

00:54:59.456 --> 00:55:02.586
to source in that food each
day to do that and it has to be

00:55:02.586 --> 00:55:05.466
at such a cost that allows
you to meet the needs

00:55:05.466 --> 00:55:07.356
of all those students,
same thing here

00:55:07.356 --> 00:55:08.566
at these institutions.

00:55:08.986 --> 00:55:11.796
And so in Los Angeles, the LA
Food Policy Councilor proposed

00:55:11.796 --> 00:55:13.616
and they called the Good
Food Purchasing Pledge

00:55:14.056 --> 00:55:18.086
which commits these institutions
to purchasing from local growers

00:55:18.086 --> 00:55:22.716
and local owners and
sourcing their food as much

00:55:22.716 --> 00:55:25.186
as possible from our own region.

00:55:25.186 --> 00:55:28.126
And I think those types of
activities have to occur

00:55:28.266 --> 00:55:32.176
if we're going to shift
from these larger sort

00:55:32.176 --> 00:55:35.216
of sociopolitical systems
that are destroying

00:55:35.216 --> 00:55:36.816
in many ways our food system.

00:55:36.816 --> 00:55:39.486
And yes I agree that we are--
we are incentivized to purchase

00:55:39.486 --> 00:55:40.746
from other countries
and whatnot.

00:55:41.126 --> 00:55:42.986
And we also have to
appreciate what that does

00:55:43.156 --> 00:55:44.516
and how it also helps to lift.

00:55:44.516 --> 00:55:46.026
It can contribute too,

00:55:46.026 --> 00:55:47.706
but it can also lift
people out of poverty.

00:55:47.956 --> 00:55:50.146
So I think it's about sort
of taking a step back,

00:55:50.146 --> 00:55:52.966
looking at the systems approach
or taking a systems approach

00:55:52.966 --> 00:55:56.576
to understanding scale and then
figuring out how we're going

00:55:56.576 --> 00:56:00.836
to re-localize our food
systems if we're actually going

00:56:00.836 --> 00:56:03.026
to achieve equity and
close those disparities.

